          </div>
          <div>
            <label class="block text-sm font-semibold text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-1.5">End Date</label>
            <input type="date" data-date-difference-calculator-target="endDate" data-action="input->date-difference-calculator#calculate" class="w-full">
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-50 to-indigo-50 dark:from-blue-900/20 dark:to-indigo-900/20 rounded-2xl p-6">
          <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-5">Results</h2>
          <div class="space-y-3">
            <div class="flex justify-between items-center">
              <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Days</span>
              <span class="text-xl font-bold text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400" data-date-difference-calculator-target="resultDays">&mdash;</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex justify-between items-center">
              <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Weeks</span>
              <span class="text-xl font-bold text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400" data-date-difference-calculator-target="resultWeeks">&mdash;</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex justify-between items-center">
              <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Months</span>
              <span class="text-xl font-bold text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400" data-date-difference-calculator-target="resultMonths">&mdash;</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex justify-between items-center">
              <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Years</span>
              <span class="text-xl font-bold text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400" data-date-difference-calculator-target="resultYears">&mdash;</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <button data-action="click->date-difference-calculator#copy" class="mt-6 w-full px-4 py-2.5 bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-600 to-indigo-600 hover:from-blue-700 hover:to-indigo-700 text-white rounded-xl shadow-sm shadow-blue-500/20 hover:shadow-md hover:shadow-blue-500/25 transition-all duration-200 focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-blue-500 focus:ring-offset-2 text-sm font-medium">Copy Results</button>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mb-8"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_results" %></div>

    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Date Difference Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Select a start date and an end date using the date pickers above. The calculator instantly computes the difference and displays it in multiple units: total days, total weeks (with a decimal for partial weeks), total months (with a decimal for partial months), and total years (with a decimal for partial years). This makes it easy to understand durations in whichever unit is most useful for your purpose.
      </p>
      <p>
        The calculator works for any date range, whether the dates are days apart or decades apart. It correctly handles months with different numbers of days, leap years, and crossing year boundaries. You can use it to count down to an event, calculate the length of a project, or find out how long ago something happened.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Common Uses for Date Calculations</h2>
      <p>
        Date difference calculations come up frequently in everyday life and professional contexts. Project managers use them to determine project timelines and deadlines. HR departments calculate employee tenure and benefit eligibility periods. Parents track their children's ages in weeks or months. Real estate professionals calculate the number of days a property has been on the market. Legal professionals compute filing deadlines, statute of limitations periods, and contract durations.
      </p>

      <h3>Understanding Date Math</h3>
      <p>
        The total number of days is the most straightforward calculation: it is the absolute difference between the two dates measured in 24-hour periods. Weeks are calculated by dividing the total days by 7. Months and years are more complex because months vary from 28 to 31 days. The calculator uses calendar months, meaning it counts how many times the same day-of-month occurs between the two dates, with the remaining days expressed as a decimal fraction.
      </p>

      <h3>Tips for Planning with Dates</h3>
      <p>
        When planning events or deadlines, always verify the exact number of days rather than estimating. Months are not interchangeable units of time because their lengths vary. Two months could be 59 days (February and March) or 62 days (July and August). For critical deadlines, count the actual calendar days to avoid surprises. This calculator eliminates guesswork by providing precise results for any date pair.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How do I calculate the number of days between two dates?</h3>
      <p>
        Subtract the earlier date from the later date. Our calculator does this instantly, accounting for varying month lengths and leap years. The result shows the total number of calendar days between the two dates, not counting the start date itself.
      </p>

      <h3>Does the calculator count weekends and holidays?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes, this calculator counts all calendar days including weekends and holidays. It provides the total elapsed time between two dates. If you need only business days, you would need to exclude Saturdays, Sundays, and any applicable holidays from the total.
      </p>

      <h3>How are months calculated between two dates?</h3>
      <p>
        Months are counted as complete calendar months. For example, from January 15 to March 15 is exactly 2 months. From January 15 to March 10 is 1 month and 23 days. The remaining days after the last complete month are shown separately.
      </p>

      <h3>Can I calculate the difference for dates in the past?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes, the calculator works for any two dates regardless of whether they are in the past, present, or future. Enter a historical date and today's date to find out how long ago an event occurred, or enter two future dates to plan ahead.
      </p>

      <h3>How does the calculator handle leap years?</h3>
      <p>
        The calculator fully accounts for leap years. February has 29 days in leap years and 28 days in common years. This affects the total day count and the month/day breakdown. All calculations use the actual calendar, so results are always accurate.
      </p>
    </article>

